column1: What will Chinese ride-hailing company DiDi's end-of-day market capitalization be on 31 December 2021?
column5: ['Less than $25 billion', 'Between $25 billion and $40 billion, inclusive', 'More than $40 billion but less than $55 billion', 'Between $55 billion and $70 billion, inclusive', 'More than $70 billion', 'DiDi will cease to be listed on a US stock exchange before 1 January 2022']

column6: First to walk: Chinese ride-sharing firm Didi announced this morning that it's delisting from the NYSE.

So, DiDi to delist from NYSE, and move to The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong (HKEX). However, it's not obvious if the procedure will be as smooth or even possible yet. Because HKEX has more requirement (such as proof of profitability) than that of NYSE. What will happen in 6 months to DiDi? I don't know. But for the sake of this question, I don't think we see improvement in price. So, bin 2 will most likely be the final outcome. Around 30 BUSD?!

https://www.reuters.com/technology/didi-global-start-work-delisting-new-york-pursue-ipo-hong-kong-2021-12-03/ This piece says they won't be done delisting until mid-2022. Story also says the effect on its value is not yet clear--could go down on lack of confidence, or could go up if easing of Chinese regulators' pressure improves the domestic prospects in China. Going with Door Number One for now, but still operating on hunches rather than data.
Based on most recent market cap assuming 50% annualized vol.

https://fortune.com/2021/07/06/didi-shares-plunge-china-delay-ipo-data-concerns/ I think the crackdown won't be a lasting issue and by the end of the year with some "loosening" the stock price jumps, hence +40 B$ market cap.

Didi currently has a market cap of 39B. Given the current crackdown from China on Tech Stocks, and the risks inherent I see it more likely that stock declines then increases. That being said irrational things can happen and the stock being close to 40B means it's more likely it goes above 40B than below 25B. Also possible but not probable is that Didi is delisted. Given the massive losses for US Shareholders in this situation, I think this is the least likely scenario.
re-allocaiting some to the de-listing option
Assuming a 50% annualized vol with no directional assumption

If it goes private, of course its market cap will skyrocket. But I'm not sure it will manage till the end of year. Besides, stocks are going up significantly in any part of the world till the Covid thing is over and people know where they new jobs are coming from.
Do not see a significant bounce back in 2021
I believe if it gets delisted is because of the US government, and not the CCP.

While the recent has been severe, I feel a strong recovery may take place. The current stock is $8.24, and it would only have to rise to $8.62 to be within the $40B category, so this is most possible. It would have to drop 1/3 in market cap to be in the first category. While this is possible (given the recent hit of ~42%), it is unlikely this will occur again, as it was environment changes that primarily brought on the drop, not business practice. Alternatively, the stock instability may cause further drop in price, so this option should not be ruled out completely.
